dict.string: Add, search and view items in a TaskPaper document

import sys, os from subprocess import check_output
readme = check_output('/usr/libexec/PlistBuddy -c "Print readme" info.plist', shell=True) settings_summary = check_output('./calls.scpt "getSettingsSummary"', shell=True) workflow_version = os.environ['SemVer']
msg = """ # TaskPaper Workflow -v %(workflow_version)s #
%(readme)s
# Settings #
%(settings_summary)s
""" % locals()
sys.stdout.write(msg)

# A normal file filter seems never show results until you start typing. Here is a hand rolled one.
from subprocess import check_output import os import sys import json
find_cmd = "mdfind \"kMDItemContentType == 'com.taskpaper.text'\"" path_list = check_output(find_cmd, shell=True).split('\n')
items = [] for path in path_list: if '/Library/Application Support/TaskPaper/Configurations/' in path: continue
items.append({ 'uid': path, 'title': os.path.basename(path).split('.')[0], 'subtitle': path, 'arg': path, 'icon': { 'path': 'icon.png' } })
sys.stdout.write(json.dumps({'items': items}))

# Keywords #
- d:setdoc configure the TaskPapar document - d:help show a brief summary of commands and settings - d:setremind view, change or disable the reminder search
- do open the workflow’s TaskPaper document - do <task> create a new task - domail create tasks from emails selected in Apple’s Mail app.
- dos search for and then select a projects, task or note - dop search for and then focus on a project - doss select and apply a search saved from the document - dot search for and then append a tag to any current search. Use the modifier _cmd-return_ to instead clear the search before appending the tag.
- dopr open resources associated with a project or to add a folder or alias resource if none exist.
# Modifiers # (return) operate on a project (cmd-return) operate on the Inbox (shift-return) operate on the Stack
